{"id":"1006.3257","submitter":"Eric Bertin","authors":"Jean-Christophe G\\'eminard, Eric Bertin","title":"Aging of the frictional properties induced by temperature variations","comments":"8 pages, 5 figures, final version, to appear in Phys. Rev. E","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. E 82, 056108 (2010)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevE.82.056108","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.stat-mech","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The dry frictional contact between two solid surfaces is well-known to obey\nCoulomb friction laws. In particular, the static friction force resisting the\nrelative lateral (tangential) motion of solid surfaces, initially at rest, is\nknown to be proportional to the normal force and independent of the area of the\nmacroscopic surfaces in contact. Experimentally, the static friction force has\nbeen observed to slightly depend on time. Such an aging phenomenon has been\naccounted for either by the creep of the material or by the condensation of\nwater bridges at the microscopic contacts points. Studying a toy-model, we show\nthat the small uncontrolled temperature changes of the system can also lead to\na significant increase of the static friction force.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 16 Jun 2010 16:07:07 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 4 Oct 2010 12:15:51 GMT"}],"update_date":"2010-11-16"}
